[{"id":"VR715725","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows the elliptical orbits of two asteroids about the same star. Asteroid 1 is closest to the start at a point labeled P. Asteroid 2 is closest to the start at a point labeled Q. A note indicates the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR715725.g02.svg\"/></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two small asteroids, Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, are in elliptical orbits about the same star, as shown in the figure. The asteroids interact gravitationally with the star, but exert negligible gravitational forces on each other. Points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P \"><math alttext=\"P \" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi></math></span></span> are where asteroids <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, respectively, are the closest to the star, and Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is passing through Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> at the same instant that Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is passing through Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi></math></span></span>. Which of the following claims about the asteroids-star system’s total angular momentum <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L sub system\"><math alttext=\"L sub system\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mtext>sys</mtext></msub></math></span></span> about the star is correct, and what evidence supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR715725_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L sub system\"><math alttext=\"L sub system\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mtext>sys</mtext></msub></math></span></span> remains constant. The acceleration of each asteroid is independent of its mass.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L sub system\"><math alttext=\"L sub system\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mtext>sys</mtext></msub></math></span></span> remains constant. The gravitational force on each asteroid does not result in a torque about the star.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L sub system\"><math alttext=\"L sub system\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mtext>sys</mtext></msub></math></span></span> has a maximum magnitude when the asteroids are at points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P \"><math alttext=\"P \" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi></math></span></span>. These are the locations where the asteroids’ speeds are greatest.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L sub system\"><math alttext=\"L sub system\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mtext>sys</mtext></msub></math></span></span> has a maximum magnitude when the asteroids are at points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi></math></span></span>. These locations are where the asteroids are the closest to the star.</p>"],"answer":1}]